{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee7607bb-1693-42e9-a53c-8e590167c447","content":"## What Happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class span support** with implicit conversions from `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` participating in overload resolution. This changes which `Contains` the compiler picks:\n\n| | .NET 9 / C# 13 | .NET 10 / C# 14 |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Resolves to** | `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` | `MemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` |\n\nThe `MemoryExtensions` overload wins because `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is a more specific match for `int[]` than `IEnumerable<int>`, and it has an `IEquatable<T>` constraint.\n\n**The problem:** `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot be boxed, used with reflection, or represented in expression trees. The expression-tree interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) fails at runtime because it cannot invoke a method taking a ref-struct parameter.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks `Enumerable.Contains` again. Two options:\n\n**Option A — Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly (static syntax):**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth force the compiler back to the `Enumerable` overload, which uses `IEnumerable<T>` — fully supported in expression trees and the interpreter.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b9dfcfd-3667-4bb5-ba08-f4dd04e010c7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant cha